Here's how to implement all three:

### 1. Custom "Cancel" back button — in `EditProductPage.xaml`

```xml
<ContentPage xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/dotnet/2021/maui"
             xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2009/xaml"
             x:Class="MyApp.Views.EditProductPage">

    <Shell.BackButtonBehavior>
        <BackButtonBehavior TextOverride="Cancel"
                            Command="{Binding BackCommand}" />
    </Shell.BackButtonBehavior>

    <!-- your form content -->
</ContentPage>
```

### 2. ViewModel back command — triggers the same confirmation logic

```csharp
public partial class EditProductViewModel : ObservableObject
{
    [ObservableProperty]
    bool hasUnsavedChanges;

    [RelayCommand]
    async Task Back()
    {
        if (HasUnsavedChanges)
        {
            bool discard = await Shell.Current.DisplayAlert(
                "Unsaved Changes",
                "You have unsaved changes. Discard them?",
                "Discard", "Stay");
            if (!discard) return;  // cancel navigation
        }
        await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("..");
    }
}
```

### 3. Guard the hardware/gesture back — in `AppShell.xaml.cs`

The custom button handles its own path, but the user can also swipe back or press the hardware back button. Guard that in `OnNavigating`:

```csharp
protected override async void OnNavigating(ShellNavigatingEventArgs args)
{
    base.OnNavigating(args);

    if (args.Source == ShellNavigationSource.Pop
        && Shell.Current.CurrentPage is EditProductPage page
        && page.BindingContext is EditProductViewModel vm
        && vm.HasUnsavedChanges)
    {
        var deferral = args.GetDeferral();

        bool discard = await page.DisplayAlert(
            "Unsaved Changes",
            "You have unsaved changes. Discard them?",
            "Discard", "Stay");

        if (!discard)
            args.Cancel();

        deferral.Complete();
    }
}
```

**Key points:**
- `GetDeferral()` is required because the confirmation is async — without it the navigation completes before the dialog returns.
- `args.Cancel()` stops navigation when the user taps "Stay."
- `BackButtonBehavior.TextOverride` replaces the back arrow with "Cancel" text.
- The `Command` on `BackButtonBehavior` bypasses `OnNavigating`, so both paths need the guard logic (the command handles it inline, `OnNavigating` catches swipe/hardware back).
